  "theory": "The Intel 8051 is an 8-bit microcontroller developed by Intel in 1980. It is the founding member of the MCS-51 family and remains the most widely used embedded microcontroller architecture globally.\n\nKey Features:\n- CPU: 8-bit processor with a Harvard architecture (separate program and data memory)\n- Program Memory: 4 KB on-chip ROM (expandable to 64 KB external)\n- Data Memory: 128 bytes on-chip RAM (expandable to 64 KB external)\n- I/O: 4 bidirectional 8-bit ports (P0, P1, P2, P3) = 32 I/O lines total\n- Timers: Two 16-bit programmable timers/counters (T0, T1)\n- Serial Port: One full-duplex UART (Universal Asynchronous Receiver/Transmitter)\n- Interrupts: 5 interrupt sources (2 external INT0, INT1; 2 timer TF0, TF1; 1 serial)\n- Oscillator: On-chip, designed for use with a crystal between XTAL1 and XTAL2\n\nPort Functions:\n- Port 0 (Pins 32-39): General purpose I/O or multiplexed low-order address/data bus (AD0-AD7) in external memory mode. It requires external pull-up resistors.\n- Port 1 (Pins 1-8): General purpose I/O. In the 8052 variant, P1.0 and P1.1 serve as T2 and T2EX.\n- Port 2 (Pins 21-28): General purpose I/O or high-order address bus (A8-A15) in external memory mode. Has internal pull-ups.\n- Port 3 (Pins 10-17): General purpose I/O with alternate functions: RXD, TXD, INT0, INT1, T0, T1, WR, RD.\n\nControl Pins:\n- RST (Pin 9): A high level on this pin for two machine cycles resets the microcontroller.\n- EA/VPP (Pin 31): External Access. When held low, the CPU executes code from external ROM. When high, it executes from internal ROM. Also used as programming voltage (VPP=12.5V) during ROM programming.\n- ALE/PROG (Pin 30): Address Latch Enable. Pulses high during the first half of each external memory cycle to latch the low-order address from Port 0. Also used as the programming pulse input during EPROM programming.\n- PSEN (Pin 29): Program Store Enable. Active-low output signal for enabling external program memory (ROM/EPROM). It pulses twice per machine cycle during external code fetch.\n- XTAL1 (Pin 19): Input to the inverting amplifier of the internal oscillator.\n- XTAL2 (Pin 18): Output of the inverting amplifier of the internal oscillator.",
  "keyPoints": [
    "40-pin DIP package with Harvard architecture (separate code and data memory).",
    "Port 0 is open-drain and multiplexed as AD0-AD7 in external memory mode; needs pull-ups.",
    "Port 3 has the most alternate functions: serial port (RXD, TXD), interrupts, timers, and memory control (RD, WR).",
    "EA pin (pin 31) must be HIGH for internal ROM execution and LOW for external ROM.",
    "ALE pulses once per machine cycle; PSEN pulses twice per machine cycle (for external program fetches).",
    "RST requires a high for at least 2 machine cycles to reset the device."
  ],
